<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-420  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 420.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 18 1989 v3 n51 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ADP faces lean budgets, tight controls; changes ahead for PentagonADP management. (the Department of Defense's data processingplans) (1990 Forecast)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob; Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Defense Department will likely experience budget cuts andmore restrictions on how it spends its money through the 1990s,and data processing managers in the DOD will have the way they buysystems altered by the 1990 Defense Appropriations Act.andO;Industrial fund accounts could be used in the past to buy systems,and extra funds could be transferred from operations andmaintenance accounts if needed.andP;  Now the DOD is required to usedirect procurement appropriations, which is intended to increaseaccountability and auditing.andP;  The Army is not affected as much asthe Navy and Air Force by the restrictions because many of itsprograms now run on direct appropriations.andP;  The Navy Regional DataAutomation Centers are now limited to software development only,but they may be used more for processing functions.andP;  The effect ofthe funding changes on the services is discussed.andM;ne</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Management of EDPGovernment AgencyMilitaryEquipment AcquisitionGovernment RegulationOutlookUnited States. Department of Defense.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>